_[Original issue](https://code.google.com/p/guava-libraries/issues/detail?id=1308) created by **simschla** on 2013-02-27 at 11:29 AM_

---

The current implementation of Closer.close() throws an IOException in the declaration.

The suggested use of Closer according to javadoc in JDK 6 says:

Closer closer = Closer.create();
try {
&nbsp;&nbsp;//register stuff here...
} catch (Throwable e) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;// register rethrows
} finally {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;closer.close(); //problem here
}

the problem is that close() throws an IOException, so what I really have to do is:
Closer closer = Closer.create();
try {
&nbsp;&nbsp;//register stuff here...
} catch (Throwable e) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;// register rethrows
} finally {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;try {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;closer.close(); //problem here
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;} catch (IOException ioe) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;//suppress, but is needed due to close's declaration
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}
}

because of this, Closer is not really a substitute for Closeables.closeQuietly().

