I haven't seen any open discussions concerning this issue; the closest issue involved some other issue entirely while ultimately referring to the Constraint interface as a dead end:

https://github.com/google/guava/issues/430

Even from its documentation, there seems to be the implication that any instance of Constraint should be tightly coupled with Collection types.

However, it seems that Constraint would be related more so with Predicate; it seems as if, for every predicate implementation, there is a corresponding constraint.

Consider the following:
- Predicates.nonNull.apply(x)
- Constraints.nonNull.checkElement(x)

The two above would seem to respectively degenerate to:
- return x != null
- if (x != null)
  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return x;
  &nbsp;&nbsp;throw new IllegalArgumentException(msg);

I would propose decoupling Constraint from Collection entirely, and having it stand on its own, checking its arguments without the notation that said argument is of a collection.

With Constraint as a loosely coupled check, any argument errors become IllegalArgumentExceptions since Constraint is not attempting to associate errors to, say, a Collection that should not contain non-null arguments; Constraint would not have to throw any run-time exception aside from IllegalArgumentException.

Also, to avoid instances where there is such tightly-coupled methods as:

boolean isValid(x) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// return true if valid
}

x valid(x) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// An analogous implementation of:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;if (isValid(x))
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return x;
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;throw iae(msg(x));
}

Constraint could also provide (and/or expose) its relation:

Object x = Constraint.apply(x);
&nbsp;// rename of Constraint.checkElement; checkElement implies Collections

boolean holds = Constraint.accepts(x);
&nbsp;// So a predicate doesn't have to do this.

String toString = Constraint.toString()
&nbsp;// a meaningful description of this constraint's condition.

With this, applying a constraint to an argument becomes analogous to:

return Preconditions.checkArgument(
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;constraint.accepts(x),
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"%s does not satisfy the conditions of this constraint: %s",
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;new Object[] {x, constraint.toString()});

Implementing a constraint's accepts(x) and toString() operations from a Predicate, p, and a String description, toString, of the constraint becomes:

boolean accepts(x) {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return p.apply(x);
}

String toString() {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return toString;
}

I would imagine that Constraint would be moved to package, com.google.common.base.Constraint, and I would hope that it would help eliminate the need for having two tightly-coupled methods for checking an argument.

Thank you.

