Typical usage of Optional.get is combined with if/else statement:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;final Optional&lt;T> optional = ...;

```
    if (optional.isPresent()) {
        return optional.get();
    } else {
        return fallBackService.get(...);
    }
```

However in examples for haskell/scala usage of optional often demonstrated with using match/case statements (and it looks quite nice). Given that in java switch/case on booleans isn't allowed what about if optional would have enumeration of states similar to next ones(code inside Optional):
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public static enum CASE {
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;ABSENT, PRESENT
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;};

```
public CASE instance() {//this method also could be abstract in Optional and overridden with simple returns in child classes 
    return isPresent() ? CASE.PRESENT : CASE.ABSENT;
}
```

and then client code could be updated to look like following:
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;final Optional&lt;T> optional = ...;

```
    switch (optional.instance()) {
      case ABSENT: return optional.get();
      case PRESENT: return fallBackService.get(...);
    }
```

In some cases it could improve readability (in this particular example usage of fallBackService could be replaced with Supplier, I used it for the sake of example)

